"PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl",
) ;

TEXT(beginproblem()) ;
$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 0 ;


$a = list_random(2, 3);
$b = list_random(11, 13);
$c = list_random(5, 7);
$d = list_random(17, 19);

$e = $a *$c;
$f = $b * $c - $a * $d;
$g = $b * $d;
$h = $b * $c + $a * $d;

BEGIN_TEXT
We know that \(y_1(x)=e^{\frac{$d}{$c} x}\) is a solution to the differential equation 
\($e D^2y + $f D y - $g y=0\) for \( x \in (-\infty,\infty)\).
Use the method of reduction of order to find a second solution 
to \($e D^2y + $f D y - $g y=0\) for \( x \in (-\infty,\infty)\).
$PAR

(a) After you reduce the second order equation by making the substitution \( w = u'\), you get a first order equation of the form 
$BR \(w' = f(x,w) = \)\{ans_box(3,60)\}.$BR
$BBOLD Note: $EBOLD Make sure you use a lower case w, (and don't use w(t), it confuses the computer).
$BR $BR 
(b) A second solution to \($e D^2y + $f D y - $g y=0\) for \( x \in (-\infty,\infty)\) is   $BR
\(y_2(x) =\) \{ ans_rule(40) \}.

END_TEXT


$diffeqAns = FEQ("-$h w/$e ");


ANS(fun_cmp( $diffeqAns,var=>['x','w']));
ANS(fun_cmp("c*e^(-($b/$a) x)", vars=>"x",params => ['c']));



